[[Image:Double-crested Cormorant at Hayward Regional Shoreline in California.jpg|thumb|[[Double-crested cormorant]] (''Phalacrocorax auritus'') at Shoreline]]
'''Hayward Regional Shoreline''' is a [[regional park]] located on the shores of the [[San Francisco Bay]] in [[Hayward, California]]. It is part of the [[East Bay Regional Park District|East Bay Regional Parks system]]. The 1,713 acre park extends to the shores of [[San Lorenzo, California|San Lorenzo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanlorenzoexpress.com/shoreprk.htm |title=Hayward Regional Shoreline |publisher=Sanlorenzoexpress.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-12}}</ref> Part of the park is former commercial salt flats purchased in 1996.<ref>{{cite web|author=Alex Barnum |url=http://articles.sfgate.com/1996-02-09/news/17768311_1_salt-ponds-salt-marsh-bay-bridge |title=Hayward Marsh to Be Saved / State buys salt flats at foot of San Mateo Bridge - SFGate |publisher=Articles.sfgate.com |date=1996-02-09 |accessdate=2014-04-12}}</ref> A former landfill, now capped with soil and plants, is located in the park. The park includes the 250 acre tidal wetland, Cogswell Marsh, and the 364 acre Oro Loma Marsh (constructed in 1997).<ref>{{cite web|author=Tom Stienstra |url=http://www.sfgate.com/outdoors/sundaydrive/article/Hayward-Shoreline-it-s-flat-beautiful-3743967.php |title=Hayward Shoreline - it's flat beautiful |publisher=SFGate |date=2012-07-29 |accessdate=2014-04-12}}</ref> Located to the south of the park is the [[Hayward Shoreline Interpretive Center]], which provides information on the Bay shore habitats. The [[San Francisco Bay Trail]] runs through the park, which connects the park with [[San Lorenzo Creek]].
[[Image:Long-billed Curlew at Hayward Shoreline.jpg|left|thumb|[[Long-billed curlew]]]]
